ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">It=E2=80=99s hard to ignore the sensation that we=E2=80=99re living thr=
ough strange days, with cultural
micro-convulsions occurring at nearly breakneck speed. To wit: It seemed li=
ke only a few weeks ago that Congress prioritized its stewardship of our na=
tional purse, USAID stood as an heirloom of <strong>Kennedy</strong>-era in=
ternationalism, and the body of water along Florida=E2=80=99s western coast=
 was inarguably known as the Gulf of Mexico.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Simi=
larly, it wasn=E2=80=99t so long ago that <strong>Elon Musk
</strong>seemed like a lonely zillionaire=E2=80=94largely a threat only to =
himself and the denizens of X, the platform not <em>so </em>long ago known =
as Twitter. Back in the quaint days of a couple <em>months </em>ago, <stron=
g>Bobby Kennedy Jr. </strong>was a Covid-era quack and drive-by presidentia=
l candidate most notable for his recent digital tryst with <strong>Olivia N=
uzzi</strong>. For his part, <strong>Pete Hegseth </strong>was a pretty boy=
 TV host with a <strong>Luke Perry </strong>streak, and
<strong>Karen Bass </strong>seemed like a shoe-in to win reelection as Los =
Angeles mayor. Time <em>flies</em>. When was the last time you read about <=
strong>Kamala Harris </strong>or <strong>Tim Walz</strong>? The erstwhile t=
icket members now seem like minor figures from a distant civilization.</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Th=
e shock and awe of the second <strong>Trump </strong>era has been arresting=
 in more ways than one, with endless observers
hypothesizing about when a new chapter will begin=E2=80=94one perhaps catal=
yzed by Democratic resistance or some behind-the-scenes fracturing within t=
he G.O.P. But I wondered whether a more insidious threat had already emerge=
d: Earlier this month, I=E2=80=99d learned that the administration was kick=
ing the tires on closing the carried interest loophole, the mother=E2=80=99=
s milk of the ~$6 <em>trillion</em> private equity industry.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p=
